  "163": {
    "text": "The quantized linear layer: stores weights as INT8 integers (1 byte each) instead of FP32 floats (4 bytes each). A single scale factor maps between the two representations.",
    "hash": "4dc60741"
  },
  "164": {
    "text": "Takes a trained FP32 linear layer and quantizes its weights.",
    "hash": "c6f83bf2"
  },
  "166": {
    "text": "Get the FP32 weight matrix.",
    "hash": "f998db9f"
  },
  "167": {
    "text": "Compute the scale factor: map the weight range [-max, +max] to [-127, +127]. This single scalar is the key \u2014 it determines the precision of the quantization.",
    "hash": "c992b589"
  },
  "168": {
    "text": "Round to nearest integer and cast to INT8. Each weight now fits in 1 byte instead of 4. The <code>register_buffer</code> saves it as a non-parameter tensor (no gradients).",
    "hash": "54b4244c"
  },
  "169": {
    "text": "Store the scale factor for dequantization during inference.",
    "hash": "b13e9ab7"
  },
  "170": {
    "text": "Carry over bias if the original layer had one (ours don't).",
    "hash": "88995ffb"
  },
  "172": {
    "text": "Forward: dequantize on-the-fly by casting back to float and multiplying by scale. In production, INT8 matmul kernels avoid this cast entirely \u2014 they compute directly in integer arithmetic.",
    "hash": "a87869a2"
  },
  "173": {
    "text": "Cast INT8 to float, multiply by scale, then do the matrix multiply. Mathematically: <code>x @ (W_int8 * scale)^T</code>. The approximation error is small because neural network weights are typically well-distributed.",
    "hash": "d5e435df"
  },
